entry.title: Don't bounds-check a history API navigation's offset in the renderer
entry.content:
When a history API navigation occurs (e.g., history.go(-2)), we

currently check whether the given offset is in-bounds before sending

the navigation to the browser. The spec and WPT expect an async step

to occur (i.e., going to the browser) so that we can take into

account any pending back/forward navigations in offset calculation.



However, when a history API navigation begins, we pause virtual time

if the navigation is in-bounds only. If we can't check that in

the renderer, we need of notifying the renderer that a history API

navigation was out of bounds so that we can unpause virtual time.

Add a case to the TraverseCancelled() message to unpause virtual

time and call it for out-of-bounds history API navigations.

(Note that TraverseCancelled() is currently only used for navigation

API traversals, but there's nothing stopping us from using the same

plumbing for this case).



This change gives us the correct behavior when history.back()

and history.forward() are called in rapid succession while at the

front of the back/forward list. The forward() should be calculated

from the pending entry for the back() navigation, resulting in

the two navigations cancelling each other out. The renderer doesn't

know what the pending offset is, so it thinks the forward() is trying

to go out-of-bounds and incorrectly rejects that navigation.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Preserve would be default match from legacy system.
entry.content:
This CL adds a feature variant that preserves the would-be default

match from the legacy scoring system. `SortAndCull` is called an extra

time before the ML model is invoked in order to determine what the

default match would've been.



This also has the side effect of limiting the matches shown after ML

scoring to only the matches that would've been shown in the legacy

system.



This CL also changes the `default_match_to_preserve` from a const

pointer to absl::optional. The pointer previously pointed to a match

that potentially went out of scope when leaving `UpdateResult()` and

was accessed inside the model callback. Additionally, when the results

are re-sorted, the match at that address can change. absl::optional

still allows us to pass an empty match but ensures that match stays

constant and still exists.

entry.title: shortcuts: Limit search query length to 200 characters
entry.content:
This CL limits the max query length of a search to 200 characters using

the `maxlength` HTML attribute.



The primary purpose of this CL is to prevent performance degradation

when many lines of text are entered (usually pasted) into the search

bar.



As part of this CL, I created a new member variable called

`searchInputElement` that is queried for + saved on init. I've updated

`strictQueries` for this element to instead use the member variable.

This is primarily a cosmetic refactor, but it's possible that there

may be very slight performance gains as a result of this change.



I've also added a test for this change, checking that the maxLength

attribute has been set. We're limited in what we can test because we

can't simulate keypresses, and manually setting the value of the input

field doesn't respect the `maxlength` attribute.



Test: browser_tests gtest_filter=ShortcutCustomizationAppSearch*

entry.title: Fix `NGInlinePaintContext` for pseudo elements in first-line
entry.content:
`ComputedStyle::AppliedTextDecorations` is usually one of

following behaviors:

a. No change from parent. Inherit the same data.

b. Add a decoration.

c. Stops propagation, resetting the decorations to 0.

d. c+b, meaning resets and add a decoration.



`NGInlinePaintContext` computes decorating boxes from

`ComputedStyle::AppliedTextDecorations` from the assumptions

above.



However, pseudo elements don't have first-line styles, and

that when they appear in the first-line, `NGInlinePaintContext`

fails to compute decorating boxes. This patch fixes it not to

crash in such a situation.



Fixed: 1440213

entry.title: Reland "[SuperSize] Add ARSC Symbols."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit c8c869cf8065724c2622e300dd0fde40a1cb0f36.

unhandled chunks no longer trigger assert error, and (as updated in

this CL) will show up as symbols with name "GENERIC: type=...".



Original change's description:

> [SuperSize] Add ARSC Symbols.

>

> This CL applies our new capability to parse ARSC files (arsc_parser.py)

> to create symbols for resources.arsc in APK files.

> * Add symbols for each {String Pool, Type Spec, Type} chunks.

> * Symbol |source_path| entry is can specify package and type context,

> e.g., ".../resources.arsc/com.google.android.apps.chrome/drawable".

> * For Type chunks, NO_ENTRY pointers are extracted into a separate

> "* (placeholder)" symbols.

> * Add "Overhead: ARSC" symbol for bytes missed by the above.

>

> Details:

> * arsc_parser.py:

> * ArscStringPool: Add |role| field that's modified by owner on

> instantiation, so string pools {"root", "types", "keys"} can be

> distinguished.

> * ArscChunk:

> * Rename |padding| to |placeholder| (for NO_ENTRY pointers).

> * Add symbol_name() (separate from __str__(), which is used for

> debugging and main()) for use by Symbol creation.

> * Add labelled_children() to visit children, while providing

> text fragments to synthesize |source_path|.

> * ArscFile.VisitPreOrder(): Update to yield |path| for symbols, to

> specify |source_path|.

> * apk.py: Add CreateArscSymbols() for ARSC symbol creation.

> * archive.py: Call to apk.CreateArscSymbols(); update "Other" symbol

> creation to skip resources.arsc if needed.

> * Add new symbol type "a", or ".arsc" for ARSC.

> * Update models.py and file_format.py to accommodate.

> * Caspian: Filter new type.

> * Viewer: Add #cb-filter-arsc, .arsc-info, .arscicon.

> * Icon: Take the "other" icon, and repaint to red #ea4335.

entry.title: [UIA] Don't expose Invoke pattern for role="tab"
entry.content:
Accessibility Insights constantly highlights a violation on websites

that use the role="tab", mapped to the UIA_TabItemControlTypeId,

saying that it shouldn't support the Invoke control pattern. This is

because a UIA_TabItemControlTypeId always supports the SelectionItem

control pattern, therefore there would two control patterns available

to provide the same invocable behavior.



Here's the Accessibility Insights rule that was violated:

https://github.com/microsoft/axe-windows/blob/main/src/Rules/Library/ControlShouldNotSupportInvokePattern.cs



Heres' the UIA documentation about the Invoke control pattern:

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/framework/ui-automation/implementing-the-ui-automation-invoke-control-pattern



And here's the UIA documentation for the TabItem control, where it's explicitly

stated that it should never support the Invoke control pattern:

https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/winauto/uiauto-supporttabitemcontroltype#required-control-patterns

entry.title: [SuperSize] Make ARSC parsing more forgiving re. unhandled chunk types.
entry.content:
Previously, arsc_parser.py asserts that the only chunk types that will

be encountered have the following types:

RES_TABLE_TYPE

RES_STRING_POOL_TYPE

RES_TABLE_PACKAGE_TYPE

RES_TABLE_TYPE_TYPE

RES_TABLE_TYPE_SPEC_TYPE



The assumption was that all other types will be embedded in

RES_TABLE_TYPE_TYPE, whose details were skipped.



It turns out the assumption was wrong: In SystemWebViewGoogle.apk's

resources.arsc, RES_TABLE_PACKAGE_TYPE contains RES_TABLE_LIBRARY_TYPE.

The presence of this unhandled chunk type triggered the assert failure

above, and blocked Canary builds. This issue was resolved by reverting

crrev.com/c/4480949.



This CL makes a minimal-change fix to enable reland:

* _ArscStreamReader.NextArscChunk():

* When unhandled chunk type is found: Instead of triggering assert,

instantiate base class ArscChunk.

* Chunk sizes are known, so explicitly seek to end address.

* ArscResTableType.__init__(): Remove seek-to-end code to skip content,

now that NextArscChunk() takes care of it.

* ArscChunk.__str__(): Render content as "GENERIC: type=...".



We'll assess / implement RES_TABLE_PACKAGE_TYPE parsing later.
